      "\n  have h₁ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by sorry\n  have h₂ : ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := sorry\n  have h₃ : ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ₑ * ‖y‖ₑ := by sorry\n  calc\n    (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := h₁\n    _ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := h₂\n    _ ≤ ‖x‖ₑ * ‖y‖ₑ := h₃",
      "The continuous functional calculus `f ↦ f(a)` is an isometry, so `‖f(a)‖ = ‖f‖`.\n\n4. **`toLinearFunctional_bounded`**: The linear functional `b ↦ ⟪x, b y⟫_ℂ` has norm `≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖`.\n\n### Step 3: Reconcile Lean Definitions with Math\n\nIn Lean:\n- The continuity of `f ↦ f(a)` is ensured by `norm_cfcHom`.\n- The functional `f ↦ ⟪x, f(a) y⟫_ℂ` is `cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y`, and its norm is bounded by `‖x‖ * ‖y‖`.\n- The Riesz-Markov-Kakutani theorem is applied to `cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y ∘ (C₀ → C)` to get `cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y`.\n\nBut in Lean's definition, `cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y` is the Riesz-Markov-Kakutani measure for `(cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) ∘ (C₀ → C)` (where `C₀` is functions vanishing at infinity). However, since we are working on a compact space (the spectrum is compact), the map `(C₀ → C)` is an isomorphism (because all continuous functions are in `C₀` when the space is compact).\n\nBut Lean's `ZeroAtInfty` might make this slightly annoying to work with because it uses `C₀` as an intermediate step. So it might actually be easier to consider the case where the space is compact directly (since `spectrum ℂ a` is compact).\n\nAlternatively, perhaps in Lean, the statement `‖φ‖ = variation(μ)` holds for `φ` and `μ` related by Riesz-Markov-Kakutani, but we need to find the right statement.\n\n### Step 4: Known Bounds and Their Implications\n\nThe linear functional `f ↦ ⟪x, f(a) y⟫_ℂ` has norm `≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖` by `cfc_toLinearFunctional_bound`.\n\nBut in Lean, the Riesz-Markov-Kakutani measure is constructed from `C₀ → C`, not directly from `C`. The norm of `φ` in Lean is actually the same as the norm of `(cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) ∘ (C₀ → C)` because the map `(C₀ → C)` is an isometry when restricted to functions on a compact set (because all continuous functions are in `C₀`).\n\nBut maybe we don't need to worry about that because the norm of `φ` is `≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖`, and the variation of the associated measure `μ` is equal to `‖φ‖`.\n\n### Step 5: Use `rieszMeasure` Properties\n\nThe key property is:\n`‖φ‖ = μ.variation (univ : Set K)`, where `φ(f) = ∫ f dμ`.\n\nIn Lean's `ComplexRMS`, for `φ : C₀(K, ℂ) →L[ℂ] ℂ`, we have:\n`(rieszMeasure φ).variation univ = ‖φ‖`.\n\nSo, in `cfc_toComplexMeasure`, the `φ` is `(cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) ∘ (C₀ → C)`.\n\nBut the norm of `φ : C₀ → C` is the same as the norm of `cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y : C → C`, because `(C₀ → C)` is an isometry (on a compact space). \n\nOr perhaps the `norm` is not exactly the same? Wait, no: the `norm` of `φ : C₀ → C` is `≤` the norm of `cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y`, because we are restricting to `C₀` (which is not the entire `C`).\n\nBut in the case of a compact space like `spectrum ℂ a`, every `f : C(K, ℂ)` is in `C₀`, so the restriction is an isomorphism, and the norm of `φ` is actually equal to the norm of `cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y`.\n\nTherefore:\n`(cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation univ = ‖φ‖ = ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖`.\n\nBut Lean uses `‖x‖ₑ`, which is `‖x‖` in the case of `ℂ` (as `H` is not necessarily `ℂ`, but `‖x‖ₑ` is still `‖x‖` because it's the norm in `H`).\n\nBut in Lean, `‖x‖ₑ` is the same as `‖x‖`, because `‖x‖ₑ` is notation for `‖x‖`.\n\n### Step 6: Formal Reasoning Sketch\n\n1. `‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖` (`cfc_toLinearFunctional_bound`).\n2. `(cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation univ = ‖(cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) ∘ (C₀ → C)‖` (by properties of `rieszMeasure`).\n3. But `‖(cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) ∘ (C₀ → C)‖ ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖` because the restriction to `C₀` decreases the norm.\n4. But on compact spaces, the map `(C₀ → C)` is an isometry, so the norms are equal.\n5. So `(cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation univ = ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖`.\n\nBut in Lean, it seems that `C₀ → C` has a left inverse (the extension by zero outside the compact), which is not injective. Maybe better to use the fact that for compact spaces, the restriction map is an isometry, but this might not exist in Lean's library.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we don't need this, because we can directly use that the norm of the linear functional is bounded by `‖x‖ * ‖y‖` and that the variation of the measure is equal to the norm of the restricted functional. But we need `‖φ‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖` for `φ : C₀ → ℂ`.\n\nBut perhaps in Lean, `(C₀ → C)` is not an isometry, but it is norm-decreasing. So:\n\n`‖φ ∘ (C₀ → C)‖ ≤ ‖φ‖`, and we already have `‖φ‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖`, so:\n\n`(cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation univ = ‖φ ∘ (C₀ → C)‖ ≤ ‖φ‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖`.\n\nBut in Lean, for `φ : C → ℂ`, `(cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)`, then `φ ∘ (C₀ → C)` is our functional on `C₀`, and `(rieszMeasure (φ ∘ (C₀ → C))).variation univ = ‖φ ∘ (C₀ → C)‖ ≤ ‖φ‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖`.\n\nBut we need to find `‖φ ∘ (C₀ → C)‖ ≤ ‖φ‖`, which should follow from the fact that `C₀ → C` has norm `≤ 1`.\n\nBut `C₀ → C` is actually an isometry because every function in `C` is in `C₀` when the space is compact. But Lean does not know that `spectrum ℂ a` is compact unless we prove it (but perhaps it is already known because it is closed and bounded in `ℂ` or something).\n\nAlternatively, perhaps the `ZeroAtInfty.liftZeroAtInfty` has norm `≤ 1`.\n\nLooking into Lean's library, `ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInfty` is `(C → C₀)` but we need `(C₀ → C)`.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can use that in Lean, `ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.continuousMap` is `(C₀ → C)` and it is the left inverse of `(C → C₀)`? No, perhaps not.\n\nBut `(C → C₀)` is a right inverse of `(C₀ → C)` because `C₀` is embedded into `C`. \n\nBut perhaps `C₀ → C` has norm `≤ 1` because it is the inclusion map. \n\nIndeed, if we have a compact space `K`, then the inclusion of `C₀(K) = C(K)` into `C(K)` is the identity. \n\nBut perhaps in Lean, `spectrum ℂ a` is compact, and then `C₀(spectrum ℂ a)` is the same as `C(spectrum ℂ a)` because the functions in `C(spectrum ℂ a)` vanish at infinity (since there is no infinity).\n\nBut if Lean does not know this, it might not be trivial.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps Lean's `C₀(K)` is `{f : C(K) | f → 0 at ∞}`, and for compact `K`, this is just `{0}`. \n\nNo, that cannot be because `0` is the only function that vanishes at infinity if `K` has no infinity. \n\nBut Lean's `C₀` is not for functions on a subset of `ℝⁿ`, but for functions on any topological space, vanishing at infinity, where \"infinity\" means the complement of every compact subset.\n\nBut for `K` compact, every `f : K → ℂ` is in `C₀(K)` because the complement of `K` is empty.\n\nBut Lean's `C₀` is for `K : Type`, not for subsets. \n\nLooking closely, perhaps `spectrum ℂ a : Type` is not compact as a type, but is compact as a topological space. So `C₀(spectrum ℂ a)` is `{f : spectrum ℂ a → ℂ | ∀ ε > 0, ∃ K : Set (spectrum ℂ a), IsCompact K ∧ ∀ x ∉ K, |f x| < ε}`.\n\nBut `spectrum ℂ a` is compact, so we can take `K = univ`, and the condition becomes that for any `ε > 0`, there is no `x ∉ univ`, so the condition is vacuously true. Hence all `f : spectrum ℂ a → ℂ` are in `C₀(spectrum ℂ a)`.\n\nTherefore, the inclusion map `(C₀(spectrum ℂ a) → C(spectrum ℂ a))` is actually a bijection, and since it is continuous, it is an isomorphism.\n\nBut more concretely, the injection `(C(spectrum ℂ a) → C₀(spectrum ℂ a))` is a left inverse of `(C₀(spectrum ℂ a) → C(spectrum ℂ a))`. But perhaps Lean does not have this.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can find that the norm of `(C₀ → C)` is `1`.\n\nIn fact, for any topological space `K`, the inclusion `(C₀(K) → C(K))` is of norm `≤ 1`, because `‖f‖_C₀ = ‖f‖_C` (since the norm in `C₀` is the same as in `C`). \n\nTherefore, in general, `‖(C₀ → C)(f)‖ = ‖f‖`, and `‖(C₀ → C)‖ ≤ 1`.\n\nBut if we have that `φ : C → ℂ` is bounded by `M`, then `φ ∘ (C₀ → C)` is bounded by `M` because `‖f‖_C₀ = ‖f‖_C`.\n\nTherefore:\n`‖φ ∘ (C₀ → C)‖ ≤ ‖φ‖`, because for any `f : C₀`, `‖(C₀ → C)(f)‖ = ‖f‖`, and then `|(φ ∘ (C₀ → C))(f)| = |φ((C₀ → C)(f))| ≤ ‖φ‖ * ‖(C₀ → C)(f)‖ = ‖φ‖ * ‖f‖`.\n\nBut perhaps not, because",
      "\n  have h₁ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ =\n      (ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure (compSL C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ)\n        C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) ℂ _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)\n        (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE\n          (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap)) .variation Set.univ := by\n    rfl\n  rw [h₁]\n  have h₂ : (ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure (compSL C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ)\n      C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) ℂ _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)\n      (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE\n        (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap)).variation Set.univ\n    ≤ ‖x‖ₑ * ‖y‖ₑ := by\n    have h₃ : ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := cfc_toLinearFunctional_bound x y\n    have h₄ : ‖(compSL C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) ℂ _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)\n      (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap : C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) →L[ℂ] ℂ)‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := by\n      calc\n        ‖(compSL C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) ℂ _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)\n          (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap : C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) →L[ℂ] ℂ)‖\n        ≤ ‖(cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y : C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) →L[ℂ] ℂ)‖ := by\n          apply ContinuousLinearMap瞬LY_.bound_compL\n          <;> simp [ContinuousLinearMap.norm_le_norm]\n          <;> exact calc\n              ‖ @ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _\n                  _ _ _ _ _ _‖ ≤ 1 := by\n                have h₅ : ‖ (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _ : C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) →L[ℂ] C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ))‖ ≤ 1 := by\n                  -- Prove that the norm of the lift is at most 1\n                  apply ContinuousLinearMap瞬LY_.norm_le\n                  intro f\n                  -- For any function f in C₀, the norm of the lift is bounded by the norm of f\n                  have h₆ : ‖(@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _ f)‖ = ‖f‖ := by\n                    rfl\n                  simp_all [Complex.norm_eq_abs]\n                  <;>\n                  linarith\n                simp_all [ContinuousLinearMap.norm_coe]\n              _ = 1 := by norm_num\n          <;> norm_num\n        _ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := h₃\n    have h₅ : (ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure (compSL C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) ℂ _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)\n      (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap)).variation Set.univ\n      ≤ ‖(compSL C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) ℂ _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)\n        (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap : C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) →L[ℂ] ℂ)‖ := by\n      -- Use the property of the Riesz measure variation\n      have h₆ : (ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure (compSL C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) ℂ _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)\n        (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap)).variation Set.univ\n        = ‖(compSL C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) ℂ _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)\n          (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap : C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) →L[ℂ] ℂ)‖ := by\n        -- Use the fact that the variation of the Riesz measure is the norm of the linear map\n        apply ComplexRieszMapMeasure.norm_eq\n      rw [h₆]\n    calc\n      (ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure (compSL C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ)\n          C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) ℂ _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)\n          (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap)).variation Set.univ\n      ≤ ‖(compSL C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) ℂ _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)\n          (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap : C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) →L[ℂ] ℂ)‖ := h₅\n      _ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := h₄\n      _ ≤ ‖x‖ₑ * ‖y‖ₑ := by\n        -- Since ‖x‖ and ‖y‖ are non-negative, their product is also non-negative.\n        -- Therefore, ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ₑ * ‖y‖ₑ, as ‖x‖ₑ = ‖x‖ and ‖y‖ₑ = ‖y‖.\n        simp [norm_eq_abs, Real.ofReal_le_ofReal]\n        <;>\n        simp_all [Real.norm_eq_abs, abs_mul]\n        <;>\n        norm_cast\n        <;>\n        linarith [norm_nonneg x, norm_nonneg y]\n  exact h₂",
      "\n  have h₀ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ = ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by\n    simp [ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure_variation]\n    <;>\n    simp_all [ComplexMeasurableMap]\n    <;>\n    simp_all [MeasurableMap]\n    <;>\n    simp_all [MeasureTheory.shape_zero]\n    <;>\n    simp_all [toComplexMeasure]\n    <;>\n    simp_all [ContinuousLinearMap]\n    <;>\n    simp_all [ComplexLinearMap]\n    <;>\n    simp_all [LinearMap]\n  \n  rw [h₀]\n  have h₁ : ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := by\n    apply cfc_toLinearFunctional_bound ha x y\n  have h₂ : (‖x‖ : ℝ) * (‖y‖ : ℝ) = ‖x‖ɛ * ‖y‖ɛ := by\n    simp [norm_eq_abs, Complex.abs_ofReal, Complex.normSq_ofReal]\n    <;> norm_cast\n    <;> simp_all [Real.norm_eq_abs]\n    <;> ring_nf\n    <;> simp_all [abs_mul]\n    <;> simp_all [abs_of_nonneg]\n    <;> simp_all [norm_nonneg]\n    <;> simp_all [abs_of_nonneg]\n    <;> simp_all [norm_nonneg]\n    <;> linarith\n  have h₃ : (‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ : ℝ) ≤ ‖x‖ɛ * ‖y‖ɛ := by\n    calc\n      (‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ : ℝ) ≤ (‖x‖ : ℝ) * (‖y‖ : ℝ) := by\n        exact_mod_cast h₁\n      _ = ‖x‖ɛ * ‖y‖ɛ := by\n        rw [h₂]\n  exact_mod_cast h₃",
      "\n  have h₁ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := by\n    have h₂ : ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := cfc_toLinearFunctional_bound x y\n    have h₃ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).total_variation = Real.sqrt ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by\n      rfl\n    have h₄ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by\n      calc\n        (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).total_variation := by\n          have h₅ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).total_variation := by\n            simpa [VectorMeasure.total_variation, Real.sqrt_le_sqrt] using VectorMeasure.variation_le_total_variation (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y) Set.univ\n          exact h₅\n        _ = ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by\n          simp [h₃]\n          <;>\n          (try\n            {\n              have h₆ : 0 ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by positivity\n              have h₇ : Real.sqrt ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≥ 0 := by positivity\n              have h₈ : Real.sqrt ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ * Real.sqrt ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ = ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by\n                rw [Real.mul_self_sqrt (by positivity : 0 ≤ (‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ : ℝ))]\n              have h₉ : Real.sqrt ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ = ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by\n                nlinarith [Real.sqrt_nonneg ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖, Real.sq_sqrt (by positivity : 0 ≤ (‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ : ℝ))]\n              simp_all [h₉]\n              <;>\n              (try norm_num) <;>\n              (try linarith)\n            })\n          <;>\n          (try simp_all [Complex.norm_eq_abs]) <;>\n          (try simp_all [ContinuousLinearMap.norm]) <;>\n          (try aesop)\n    calc\n      (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := h₄\n      _ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := h₂\n  have h₅ : ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ₑ * ‖y‖ₑ := by\n    simp [normOfReal]\n    <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        have h₆ : 0 ≤ ‖x‖ := by positivity\n        have h₇ : 0 ≤ ‖y‖ := by positivity\n        have h₈ : 0 ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := by positivity\n        have h₉ : (‖x‖ : ℝ) = ‖x‖ := by simp\n        have h₁₀ : (‖y‖ : ℝ) = ‖y‖ := by simp\n        simp_all [Real.sqrt_eq_iff_sq_eq]\n        <;>\n        nlinarith [Real.sqrt_nonneg (‖x‖ : ℝ), Real.sqrt_nonneg (‖y‖ : ℝ),\n          Real.sq_sqrt (by positivity : 0 ≤ (‖x‖ : ℝ)),\n          Real.sq_sqrt (by positivity : 0 ≤ (‖y‖ : ℝ))]\n      })\n    <;>\n    (try ring_nf) <;>\n    (try simp_all [Complex.norm_eq_abs]) <;>\n    (try simp_all [ContinuousLinearMap.norm]) <;>\n    (try aesop)\n  calc\n    (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := h₁\n    _ ≤ ‖x‖ₑ * ‖y‖ₑ := h₅",
      "\n  have h₁ : ‖x‖ₑ = ‖x‖ := by simp [norm_eq_norm_e]\n  have h₂ : ‖y‖ₑ = ‖y‖ := by simp [norm_eq_norm_e]\n  have h₃ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := by\n    -- Use the fact that the variation of the measure is bounded by the norm of the linear functional\n    have h₄ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by\n      -- Apply the property of the Riesz measure\n      have h₅ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by\n        -- Use the fact that the variation of the measure is bounded by the norm of the linear functional\n        have h₆ : ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ = ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := rfl\n        -- Use the property of the Riesz measure\n        have h₇ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by\n          -- Use the fact that the variation of the measure is bounded by the norm of the linear functional\n          apply ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure_variation_le_norm\n        exact h₇\n      exact h₅\n    -- Use the bound on the norm of the linear functional\n    have h₅ : ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := by\n      apply cfc_toLinearFunctional_bound\n    -- Combine the two inequalities\n    linarith\n  -- Substitute back the original norms\n  simp_all [h₁, h₂]\n  <;>\n  norm_num\n  <;>\n  linarith",
      "...",
      "\n  have h₁ : ‖x‖ₑ * ‖y‖ₑ = ENorm.ofNorm (‖x‖ * ‖y‖) := by\n    simp [norm_mul, ENorm.ofNorm_mul]\n    <;> ring_nf\n    <;> simp_all [Real.norm_eq_abs]\n    <;> field_simp [Real.norm_eq_abs]\n    <;> ring_nf\n  \n  have h₂ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ENorm.ofNorm (‖x‖ * ‖y‖) := by\n    have h₃ : ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := cfc_toLinearFunctional_bound x y\n    have h₄ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ENorm.ofNorm (‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖) := by\n      -- Use the fact that the variation of the measure is bounded by the norm of the linear functional\n      calc\n        (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ =\n            (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ := rfl\n        _ ≤ ENorm.ofNorm (‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖) := by\n          -- Use the Riesz-Markov-Kakutani theorem to relate the variation of the measure to the norm of the linear functional\n          have h₅ : ENorm.ofNorm (‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖) = ENorm.ofNorm (‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖) := rfl\n          have h₆ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ENorm.ofNorm (‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖) := by\n            -- Use the fact that the variation of the measure is bounded by the norm of the linear functional\n            have h₇ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ =\n                (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ := rfl\n            calc\n              (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤\n                  ENorm.ofNorm (‖(compSL C₀((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) C((spectrum ℂ a), ℂ) ℂ _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)\n                    (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ℂ a) ℂ ℂ _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap)‖) := by\n                -- Use the fact that the variation of the measure is bounded by the norm of the linear functional\n                apply ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure_variation_le_ofNorm\n              _ = ENorm.ofNorm (‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖) := by\n                -- Use the fact that the composition with the zero-at-infinity map does not change the norm\n                simp [ContinuousLinearMap.norm_comp_le]\n                <;>\n                  simp_all [ContinuousLinearMap.norm_eq_zero, ContinuousLinearMap.eq_zero_iff]\n                <;>\n                  try norm_num\n                <;>\n                  try linarith\n                <;>\n                  try simp_all [ContinuousLinearMap.norm_eq_zero, ContinuousLinearMap.eq_zero_iff]\n                <;>\n                  try norm_num\n                <;>\n                  try linarith\n          exact h₆\n    calc\n      (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ENorm.ofNorm (‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖) := h₄\n      _ ≤ ENorm.ofNorm (‖x‖ * ‖y‖) := by\n        -- Use the fact that the norm of the linear functional is bounded by ‖x‖ * ‖y‖\n        gcongr\n        <;> simp_all [ContinuousLinearMap.norm_eq_zero, ContinuousLinearMap.eq_zero_iff]\n        <;> try norm_num\n        <;> try linarith\n        <;> try simp_all [ContinuousLinearMap.norm_eq_zero, ContinuousLinearMap.eq_zero_iff]\n        <;> try norm_num\n        <;> try linarith\n  \n  calc\n    (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ENorm.ofNorm (‖x‖ * ‖y‖) := h₂\n    _ = ‖x‖ₑ * ‖y‖ₑ := by\n      -- Convert ENorm back to the product of norms\n      simp_all [h₁]",
      "\n  have h₁ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by\n    have h₂ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ = ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by\n      rw [ComplexRMK.variation_rieszMeasure]\n      <;>\n      simp [Complex.norm_eq_abs]\n      <;>\n      simp_all [ContinuousLinearMap.norm_def]\n      <;>\n      norm_cast\n      <;>\n      simp_all [ContinuousLinearMap.norm_def]\n      <;>\n      norm_cast\n    rw [h₂]\n    <;>\n    simp [Complex.norm_eq_abs]\n    <;>\n    simp_all [ContinuousLinearMap.norm_def]\n    <;>\n    norm_cast\n  \n  have h₂ : ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := by\n    have h₃ : ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := by\n      calc\n        ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := by\n          -- Use the previously established bound on the linear functional\n          have h₄ : ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := by\n            exact cfc_toLinearFunctional_bound ha x y\n          exact h₄\n        _ = ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := by rfl\n    exact h₃\n  \n  have h₃ : (‖x‖ : ℝ) * ‖y‖ = ‖x‖ₑ * ‖y‖ₑ := by\n    simp [norm_eq_abs, Real.norm_eq_abs]\n    <;>\n    simp_all [Complex.norm_eq_abs]\n    <;>\n    norm_cast\n    <;>\n    simp_all [Complex.norm_eq_abs]\n    <;>\n    norm_cast\n  \n  have h₄ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖x‖ₑ * ‖y‖ₑ := by\n    calc\n      (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := h₁\n      _ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := h₂\n      _ = ‖x‖ₑ * ‖y‖ₑ := by\n        simpa [norm_eq_abs] using h₃\n  \n  exact h₄",
      "\n  have h₀ : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := by\n    apply ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure_var_le_norm\n  have h₁ : ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := by\n    apply cfc_toLinearFunctional_bound ha x y\n  calc\n    (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).variation Set.univ ≤ ‖cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‖ := h₀\n    _ ≤ ‖x‖ * ‖y‖ := h₁",
      "",
